#Text=Space Shuttle Endeavour launches for mission STS-123
#Text=Tuesday , March 11 , 2008
#Text=Space Shuttle Endeavour successfully launched this morning from Launch Complex 39A at the Kennedy Space Center , on mission STS-123 to assemble the International Space Station ( ISS ) .
#Text=Lift-off occurred at 06:28:14 UTC ( 02:28 local time ) .
#Text=On board was a crew of seven astronauts ; Mission Commander Dominic Gorie , Pilot Gregory Johnson , Robert Behnken , Michael Foreman , Richard Linnehan , Takao Doi and Garrett Reisman .
#Text=All except Reisman will return to Earth aboard Endeavour in two week 's time .
#Text=Reisman , a member of the ISS Expedition 16 and 17 crews , will remain aboard the Space Station , replacing Léopold Eyharts who launched aboard STS-122 last month .
#Text=During the 16-day mission - the longest
#Text=Shuttle flight in support of the ISS - the crew will install two major ISS components . the Kibō Pressurised Logistics Module and the Canadian Special Purpose Dexterous Manipulator ( SPDM ) .
#Text=The Kibō Pressurised Logistics Module is the first of three components which will form the Japanese Experiment Module ( JEM ) .

#Text=It will be temporarily installed on a spare docking port of the Harmony module of the Station , and will later be fitted to the main pressurised experiment module , which is slated for launch aboard STS-124 , to be flown by Discovery in late May .
#Text=SPDM , also known as Dextre , is a twin robotic arm system , or Remote Manipulator System ( RMS ) , which will be installed on the end of the Space Station 's Canadarm2 robotic arm .
#Text=It will allow complex tasks to be completed without the need for a spacewalk .
#Text=Five extra-vehicular activities are planned for the mission .
#Text=The first three of these will be to assemble , install and test the Dextre SPDM .
#Text=This will be followed by an EVA to test new tile repair techniques in the event of a Shuttle becoming damaged on a later mission .
#Text=This test comes ahead of the planned STS-125 mission to service the Hubble Space Telescope in August .
#Text=The final EVA will be to stow the Orbiter Boom Sensor System ( OBSS ) on the Space Station .

#Text=This usually remains on the Shuttle for launch and landing , however as the next mission , STS-124 , is carrying a very large payload - the JEM pressurised experiment module - the OBSS cannot be accommodated in its payload bay for launch .
#Text=Because it will be needed once the Shuttle reaches orbit , Discovery will collect the OBSS from the ISS , and return it to Earth at the end of its mission .
#Text=The OBSS is used to conduct photography of the orbiter 's heat shield , in order to check for damage , similar to that which caused the Columbia accident .
#Text=Two minor problems occurred during the launch .
#Text=Firstly , the primary Flash Evaporator System failed , resulting in a switch to the backup system , which performed normally .
#Text=The Flash Evaporator System is used to cool the Shuttle prior to the deployment of its radiators .
#Text=The radiators were deployed normally following payload bay door opening , once the Shuttle was in orbit .
#Text=The other issue was that instrumentation failed for a small number of Reaction Control System ( RCS ) thrusters , which are used to control the Shuttles attitude .
#Text=Neither problem is expected to affect the mission .

#Text=The ascent to orbit has been initially assessed as " clean " in terms of debris impacts , the only concern is a suspected birdstrike ten seconds after launch , however it is believed that Endeavour was not travelling fast enough to sustain damage .
#Text=This is the 122nd launch of the Space Shuttle , the 21st of Endeavour , and the 25th Shuttle mission to the ISS .
#Text=It also marks the ninth , and second manned , orbital launch of 2008 .
#Text=Launch occurred at night , making this the Shuttle 's 30th night launch .

#Text=This flight was originally scheduled to launch on February 14th , but after the previous mission , STS-122 , was delayed due to bad sensors inside the external fuel tank , STS-123 was pushed back to no earlier than March 11 .
